Create a new empty DataFrame called returns. This dataframe will contain the returns for each bank's stock. returns are typically defined by:

$$r_t = \frac{p_t - p_{t-1}}{p_{t-1}} = \frac{p_t}{p_{t-1}} - 1$$

In [54]:
returns = pd.DataFrame()

We can use pandas pct_change() method on the Close column to create a column representing this return value. Create a for loop that goes and for each Bank Stock Ticker creates this returns column and set's it as a column in the returns DataFrame.

In [55]:
for tick in tickers:
    returns[tick+" Return"] = df[tick]['Close'].pct_change() #Percentage Change from the Last Closing Price

Moving Averages¶

Let's analyze the moving averages for these stocks in the year 2008.

Plot the rolling 30 day average against the Close Price for Bank Of America's stock for the year 2008 https://www.investopedia.com/articles/active-trading/052014/how-use-moving-average-buy-stocks.asp

In [68]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,4))
df['BAC']['Close'].loc['2008-01-01':'2009-01-01'].rolling(window=30).mean().plot(label='30 day Avg')
df['BAC']['Close'].loc['2008-01-01':'2009-01-01'].plot(label='BAC Close')
plt.legend()
